1	\chapter{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups, sheafification and Ext}
2	\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}
3	
4	This chapter executes Phase~A steps~2--4 on the topology of opens of an arbitrary topological space, using the sheaf-compose instance of Chapter~REF as input. It supplies three pieces of infrastructure that sit immediately upstream of the genus definition (Definition~REF):
5	
6	\begin{enumerate}
7	  \item Sheafification for abelian-group-valued sheaves on opens (Phase~A step~2).
8	  \item \(\Ext\) on the same sheaf category (Phase~A step~3).
9	  \item Promotion of the structure sheaf \(\mathcal O_C\) from commutative-ring-valued to abelian-group-valued, packaging the data on which sheaf cohomology can be evaluated (Phase~A step~4 first half).
10	\end{enumerate}
11	
12	No new mathematical content is introduced here, only the typeclass plumbing and one definition. After this chapter lands, the only remaining steps in Phase~A are equipping \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\) with a \(k\)-vector-space structure and proving Serre finiteness; both are deferred to subsequent iterations.
13	
14	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and instance here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\) in Definition~REF.
15	
16	\section{Sheafification of abelian-group-valued sheaves on opens}
17	
18	\begin{theorem}\leanok
19	[Sheafification on the topology of opens, abelian-group valued]
20	  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
21	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
22	  Let \(X\) be a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of \(X\) admits sheafification for sheaves valued in the category of abelian groups.
23	\end{theorem}
24	
25	\begin{proof}
26	
27	
28	\leanok
29	  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs sheafification whenever weak sheafification holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For the topology of opens of \(X\) and the category of abelian groups, both prerequisites are already available in Mathlib (concrete-category sheafification on a small site, plus exactness of abelian-group-valued sheafification). The instance is therefore inferable; the formal task is to establish the universe pinning needed to make instance synthesis succeed.
30	\end{proof}
31	
32	\section{\(\Ext\) for sheaves on opens}
33	
34	\begin{theorem}\leanok
35	[\(\Ext\) on the topology of opens, abelian-group valued]
36	  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
37	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
38	  
39	  Let \(X\) be a topological space. Then the category of sheaves of abelian groups on the topology of opens of \(X\) admits \(\Ext\) groups.
40	\end{theorem}
41	
42	\begin{proof}
43	
44	
45	\leanok
46	  The category of abelian groups is abelian. The sheaf category inherits an abelian structure from an abelian value category once sheafification is available (Theorem~REF). Mathlib's standard construction produces \(\Ext\) from any abelian category.
47	\end{proof}
48	
49	\section{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups}
50	
51	\begin{definition}\leanok
52	[Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups]
53	  \label{def:Scheme_toAbSheaf}
54	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toAbSheaf}
55	  
56	  Let \(C\) be a scheme. The structure sheaf of \(C\), viewed as a sheaf of abelian groups on the topology of opens of the underlying topological space of \(C\), is obtained by post-composing the commutative-ring-valued structure sheaf with the forgetful composite \(\mathrm{CommRing} \to \mathrm{Ring} \to \mathrm{Ab}\) of Chapter~REF.
57	\end{definition}
58	
59	The construction uses the sheaf-compose functoriality, which requires the sheaf-compose instance from Chapter~REF. Functoriality in \(C\) is delegated to a future iteration once it is needed for naturality of the cohomology long exact sequence.
60	
61	\section{Use in the project}
62	
63	The chain \(\text{sheaf-compose} \to \text{sheafification} \to \Ext \to \text{toAbSheaf}\) unblocks the abelian-group-level definition of \(H^n(C, \mathcal O_C)\):
64	\[
65	  H^n(C, \mathcal O_C) \;:=\; \text{toAbSheaf}(C).H\,n,
66	\]
67	where \(H\) is the abstract sheaf-cohomology functor. The result is automatically an abelian group. Only two steps remain inside Phase~A:
68	
69	\begin{itemize}
70	  \item Equip \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\) with the \(k\)-module structure inherited from the \(k\)-algebra structure on \(\Gamma(C, \mathcal O_C)\) (Phase~A step~5).
71	  \item Establish finite rank via Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of proper \(k\)-schemes (Phase~A step~6).
72	\end{itemize}
73	
74	Both are deferred to iterations beyond this chapter.
75	
76	\begin{remark}[Lean implementation]
77	  The sheafification and \(\Ext\) instances are inferable from Mathlib's small-site and concrete-category APIs. The structure-sheaf promotion uses Mathlib's sheaf-compose machinery together with the forget-composite instance of Chapter~REF. The only work is universe annotation: the morphism universe of the sheaf category lives one level above the object universe, and the instances must be pinned accordingly.
78	\end{remark}
79

1	\chapter{Sheaves of \(k\)-modules: sheafification, Ext, and the structure sheaf as a sheaf of \(k\)-modules}
2	\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafModuleK}
3	
4	This chapter implements Phase~A step~5: equipping \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\) with a \(k\)-vector-space structure when \(C\) is a scheme over \(\Spec k\). The route is through the linear enrichment of the sheaf category over \(k\), which automatically provides a \(k\)-module structure on \(\Ext\) groups in any \(k\)-linear abelian category. The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every instance and definition here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\) in Definition~REF.
5	
6	The chapter splits into two parts. Sections~REF--REF provide the typeclass plumbing: sheafification and \(\Ext\) for sheaves valued in \(k\)-modules. Section~REF provides the substantive content: the \(k\)-module-valued structure sheaf for a scheme over \(\Spec k\), built from the algebra map induced by the structure morphism. Together these complete Phase~A step~5; the final remaining piece for an honest definition of genus is Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, multi-iteration).
7	
8	\section{Sheafification of \(k\)-module-valued sheaves on opens}
9	\label{sec:moduleK_prereqs}
10	
11	\begin{theorem}\leanok
12	[Sheafification on the topology of opens, \(k\)-module valued]
13	  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
14	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
15	  Let \(k\) be a commutative ring and \(X\) a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of \(X\) admits sheafification for sheaves valued in the category of \(k\)-modules.
16	\end{theorem}
17	
18	\begin{proof}
19	
20	
21	\leanok
22	  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs sheafification whenever weak sheafification holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For the topology of opens and the category of \(k\)-modules, both prerequisites are available in Mathlib. The instance is therefore inferable; the formal task is the universe pinning, mirroring the abelian-group analogue (Theorem~REF).
23	\end{proof}
24	
25	\section{\(\Ext\) for \(k\)-module-valued sheaves on opens}
26	\label{sec:moduleK_ext}
27	
28	\begin{theorem}\leanok
29	[\(\Ext\) on the topology of opens, \(k\)-module valued]
30	  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
31	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
32	  
33	  Let \(k\) be a commutative ring and \(X\) a topological space. Then the category of sheaves of \(k\)-modules on the topology of opens of \(X\) admits \(\Ext\) groups.
34	\end{theorem}
35	
36	\begin{proof}
37	
38	
39	\leanok
40	  The category of \(k\)-modules is abelian. The sheaf category inherits an abelian structure from an abelian value category once sheafification is available (Theorem~REF). Mathlib's standard construction produces \(\Ext\) from any abelian category. The universe annotation matches the morphism universe of the sheaf category, mirroring the abelian-group analogue (Theorem~REF).
41	\end{proof}
42	
43	\section{The structure sheaf of a \(\Spec k\)-scheme as a sheaf of \(k\)-modules}
44	\label{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
45	
46	This section provides the substantive content of Phase~A step~5. For \(C\) a scheme over \(\Spec k\), the structure morphism \(C \to \Spec k\) induces an algebra map \(k \to \Gamma(C, U)\) for every open \(U \subseteq C\). This equips the structure sheaf with a sheaf-of-\(k\)-modules structure.
47	
48	\subsection{The algebra map from the structure morphism}
49	
50	For each open \(U \subseteq C\), the structure morphism induces a chain of ring maps
51	\[
52	  k \xrightarrow{\cong} \Gamma(\Spec k, \top) \xrightarrow{C.\mathrm{hom}} \Gamma(C, C.\mathrm{hom}^{-1}\top) \xrightarrow{\rho} \Gamma(C, U),
53	\]
54	where \(\rho\) is the restriction along \(U \le C.\mathrm{hom}^{-1}\top = \top\).
55	
56	\begin{definition}\leanok
57	[Algebra map on a section]
58	  \label{def:Scheme_kToSection}
59	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.kToSection}
60	  
61	  Let \(k\) be a commutative ring and \(C\) a scheme over \(\Spec k\). For any open \(U\) of \(C\), define the ring map \(k \to \Gamma(C, U)\) to be the composition of the inverse of the canonical isomorphism \(\Gamma(\Spec k, \top) \cong k\), the structure morphism map on global sections, and the restriction from \(\top\) to \(U\).
62	\end{definition}
63	
64	\begin{definition}\leanok
65	[Algebra structure on a section]
66	  \label{def:Scheme_algebraSection}
67	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraSection}
68	  
69	  The ring map of Definition~REF exhibits \(\Gamma(C, U)\) as a \(k\)-algebra.
70	\end{definition}
71	
72	\begin{lemma}\leanok
73	[Defining identity for the algebra map]
74	  \label{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
75	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
76	  
77	  Under the algebra structure of Definition~REF, the structure map \(k \to \Gamma(C, U)\) equals the ring map of Definition~REF.
78	\end{lemma}
79	
80	\begin{proof}
81	  
82	  \leanok
83	  Definitionally true: converting a ring homomorphism to an algebra structure and extracting the structure map recovers the original homomorphism.
84	\end{proof}
85	
86	\subsection{Naturality of the algebra map}
87	
88	\begin{lemma}\leanok
89	[Restriction is compatible with the algebra map]
90	  \label{lem:Scheme_kToSection_naturality}
91	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.kToSection_naturality}
92	  
93	  For any inclusion \(V \le U\) of opens in \(C\), the algebra map commutes with restriction: the composition \(k \to \Gamma(C, U) \to \Gamma(C, V)\) equals the direct map \(k \to \Gamma(C, V)\).
94	\end{lemma}
95	
96	\begin{proof}
97	  
98	  \leanok
99	  Both sides factor through the structure morphism map on global sections. The remaining triangle commutes by functoriality of the presheaf on composable inclusions.
100	\end{proof}
101	
102	\begin{lemma}\leanok
103	[Algebra-map naturality]
104	  \label{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_naturality}
105	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraMap_naturality}
106	  
107	  For any inclusion \(V \le U\) of opens in \(C\) and any \(r \in k\), the restriction map sends the image of \(r\) in \(\Gamma(C, U)\) to the image of \(r\) in \(\Gamma(C, V)\).
108	\end{lemma}
109	
110	\begin{proof}
111	  
112	  \leanok
113	  Lemma~REF reduces both sides to the underlying ring map of the algebra map; Lemma~REF then closes the goal by congruence.
114	\end{proof}
115	
116	\subsection{The presheaf of \(k\)-modules and its sheaf condition}
117	
118	\begin{definition}\leanok
119	[Presheaf of \(k\)-modules from \(\mathcal O_C\)]
120	  \label{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf}
121	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKPresheaf}
122	  
123	  Define the presheaf of \(k\)-modules on \(C\) by sending each open \(U\) to the \(k\)-module \(\Gamma(C, U)\), with the \(k\)-action given by the algebra structure of Definition~REF, and on an inclusion \(V \le U\) by the restriction map viewed as a \(k\)-linear map. Functoriality reduces to the presheaf axioms of \(\mathcal O_C\).
124	\end{definition}
125	
126	\begin{theorem}\leanok
127	[Sheaf condition]
128	  \label{thm:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf}
129	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf}
130	  
131	  The presheaf of Definition~REF is a sheaf for the Grothendieck topology of opens of \(C\).
132	\end{theorem}
133	
134	\begin{proof}
135	  
136	  \leanok
137	  By the concrete-category criterion, it suffices to show that the underlying presheaf of types is a sheaf. By construction, this composite agrees on objects and morphisms with the structure sheaf viewed as a presheaf of types. The latter is a sheaf because the structure sheaf is a sheaf of commutative rings.
138	\end{proof}
139	
140	\subsection{The structure sheaf as a sheaf of \(k\)-modules}
141	
142	\begin{definition}\leanok
143	[Structure sheaf as a sheaf of \(k\)-modules]
144	  \label{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
145	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf}
146	  
147	  Bundle Definition~REF and Theorem~REF into the sheaf of \(k\)-modules on \(C\).
148	\end{definition}
149	
150	\subsection{Forget-and-recover: bridging \(k\)-module and abelian-group values}
151	
152	\begin{definition}\leanok
153	[Forget-and-recover natural iso for the \(k\)-module structure sheaf]
154	  \label{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}
155	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}
156	  
157	  Let \(C\) be a scheme over \(\Spec k\). Then forgetting the \(k\)-module structure from the sheaf of Definition~REF yields a sheaf of abelian groups canonically isomorphic to the abelian-group-valued structure sheaf of Definition~REF.
158	\end{definition}
159	
160	\begin{proof}
161	  
162	  \leanok
163	  Definitionally true: both sides evaluate at every open \(U\) to the abelian group underlying \(\Gamma(C, U)\), and the action on morphisms is the underlying restriction map on both sides.
164	\end{proof}
165	
166	\begin{lemma}\leanok
167	[Object-evaluation lemma for the presheaf of \(k\)-modules]
168	  \label{lem:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf_obj}
169	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKPresheaf_obj}
170	  
171	  For every open \(U\) of \(C\), the value of the presheaf of Definition~REF at \(U\) is the \(k\)-module with carrier \(\Gamma(C, U)\).
172	\end{lemma}
173	
174	\begin{proof}
175	  
176	  \leanok
177	  Definitionally true by construction.
178	\end{proof}
179	
180	\section{Sheaf cohomology with \(k\)-module coefficients}
181	\label{sec:HModule}
182	
183	The abstract cohomology API is formulated for sheaves of abelian groups. To obtain a \(k\)-vector-space structure on \(H^n(C, \mathcal O_C)\), we build a parallel sheaf cohomology valued in \(k\)-modules. The sheaf category of \(k\)-modules already has \(\Ext\) (Theorem~REF), and \(\Ext\) groups in any \(k\)-linear abelian category carry a canonical \(k\)-module structure.
184	
185	\begin{definition}\leanok
186	[Sheaf cohomology with \(k\)-module coefficients]
187	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule}
188	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}
189	  
190	  Let \(k\) be a field, \(C\) a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of \(k\)-modules and \(\Ext\). For a sheaf \(F\) of \(k\)-modules and \(n \in \mathbb N\), define the \(k\)-module-valued sheaf cohomology
191	  \[
192	    H^n_{\Module}(F) \;:=\; \Ext^n\bigl(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F\bigr).
193	  \]
194	  This automatically carries a \(k\)-module structure.
195	\end{definition}
196	
197	\begin{remark}[Lean implementation]
198	  The declaration uses a reducible wrapper (`abbrev` rather than `def`) so that instance synthesis sees through to the underlying \(\Ext\) group and finds both the \(k\)-module and abelian-group structures automatically. Under a non-reducible wrapper, `Module.finrank` would fail to typecheck.
199	\end{remark}
200	
201	\section{The \(H^0\) algebraic bridge}
202	\label{sec:HModule_zero}
203	
204	After Definition~REF the cohomology groups \(H^n_{\Module}(F)\) are well-defined and carry the canonical \(k\)-module structure. The next algebraic preliminary is the identification of the degree-zero piece \(H^0_{\Module}(F)\) with a \(\Hom\) group: the bridge from sheaf cohomology to representable Hom-functors.
205	
206	\begin{definition}\leanok
207	[\(H^0\) as a \(k\)-linear Hom group]
208	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
209	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
210	  
211	  Let \(k\) be a field, \(C\) a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of \(k\)-modules and \(\Ext\), and \(F\) a sheaf of \(k\)-modules. Then there is a canonical \(k\)-linear equivalence
212	  \[
213	    H^0_{\Module}(F) \;\simeq_k\; \Hom(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F).
214	  \]
215	\end{definition}
216	
217	\begin{proof}
218	  
219	  \leanok
220	  Direct from Mathlib's \(H^0\) bridge in any \(k\)-linear abelian category, applied to the sheaf category of \(k\)-modules. The \(k\)-linear enrichment is auto-inferable from the sheafification hypothesis.
221	\end{proof}
222	
223	\begin{remark}[Choice of linear equivalence]
224	  Mathlib provides three flavours of the \(\Ext^0 \simeq \Hom\) equivalence: plain, additive, and \(k\)-linear. We choose the \(k\)-linear refinement because it is the one consumed downstream: finiteness of \(H^0_{\Module}(F)\) over \(k\) is equivalent to finiteness of the Hom group, via transport along a \(k\)-linear equivalence.
225	\end{remark}
226	
227	\section{\v{C}ech cohomology of the structure sheaf}
228	\label{sec:moduleK_cech}
229	
230	This section opens Path~2 of Phase~A step~6: the \v{C}ech-cohomology approach to Serre finiteness. The \v{C}ech complex of a sheaf with respect to an indexed open cover is the standard alternating-coface complex; its cohomology in each degree lives in the category of \(k\)-modules.
231	
232	\begin{definition}\leanok
233	[\v{C}ech complex of the structure sheaf]
234	  \label{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}
235	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cechCochain_OC}
236	  
237	  Let \(C\) be a scheme over \(\Spec k\) and \(\mathcal U\) an indexed family of opens of \(C\). Define the \v{C}ech cochain complex of the structure sheaf with respect to \(\mathcal U\) to be the standard \v{C}ech complex applied to the underlying presheaf of the \(k\)-module-valued structure sheaf. This is a cochain complex valued in \(k\)-modules, indexed by \(\mathbb N\).
238	\end{definition}
239	
240	\begin{definition}\leanok
241	[\v{C}ech cohomology of the structure sheaf]
242	  \label{def:Scheme_cechCohomology_OC}
243	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cechCohomology_OC}
244	  
245	  With \((C, \mathcal U)\) as in Definition~REF, define the \(n\)-th \v{C}ech cohomology to be the \(n\)-th homology of the \v{C}ech cochain complex. The result lives in the category of \(k\)-modules.
246	\end{definition}
247	
248	\begin{remark}
249	  This section defines the \v{C}ech carriers but does not prove that \v{C}ech cohomology agrees with derived-functor cohomology. The comparison theorem requires the cover to be acyclic, and is queued for a subsequent iteration.
250	\end{remark}
251	
252	\section{Cohomology of an open in \(k\)-module flavor}
253	\label{sec:hmodule_prime}
254	
255	We introduce a second cohomology carrier: cohomology of an open, parameterised by the open set \(X\). This is the API entry point that downstream Mayer--Vietoris LES and \v{C}ech-vs-derived comparison theorems both consume.
256	
257	\begin{definition}\leanok
258	[Cohomology of an open with \(k\)-module coefficients]
259	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
260	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'}
261	  
262	  Let \(k\) be a field, \(C\) a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of \(k\)-modules and \(\Ext\), and \(F\) a sheaf of \(k\)-modules. For \(n \in \mathbb N\) and \(X\) an object of \(C\):
263	  \[
264	    H^{\prime n}(X, F) \;:=\; \Ext^n\bigl(\text{sheafified representable at }X,\; F\bigr) \;\in\; \mathrm{Type}.
265	  \]
266	  The underlying type carries a \(k\)-module structure through the same \(\Ext\) mechanism that powers \(H_{\Module}\).
267	\end{definition}
268	
269	\begin{remark}
270	  The reducible wrapper is required for the same reason as in Definition~REF: instance synthesis must see through to the underlying \(\Ext\) group.
271	\end{remark}
272	
273	\section{The \(H^0\) algebraic bridge for cohomology of an open}
274	\label{sec:hmodule_prime_zero}
275	
276	Parallel to Definition~REF, we identify the degree-zero piece of cohomology of an open with a Hom group.
277	
278	\begin{definition}\leanok
279	[\(H^0\) as a \(k\)-linear Hom group, open flavor]
280	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv}
281	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_zero_linearEquiv}
282	  
283	  Let \(k\) be a field, \(C\) a Grothendieck site, \(X\) an object of \(C\), and \(F\) a sheaf of \(k\)-modules. Then there is a canonical \(k\)-linear equivalence
284	  \[
285	    H^{\prime 0}(X, F) \;\simeq_k\; \Hom(\text{sheafified representable at }X,\; F).
286	  \]
287	\end{definition}
288	
289	\begin{proof}
290	  
291	  \leanok
292	  Direct from the \(H^0\) bridge in any \(k\)-linear abelian category, applied to the sheaf category of \(k\)-modules.
293	\end{proof}
294	
295	\begin{remark}
296	  Together with Definition~REF, the two \(H^0\) bridges provide the algebraic preliminaries for both the global and open-local cohomology theories. The substantive Mayer--Vietoris LES theorem is built on these carriers in Chapter~REF.
297	\end{remark}
298	
299	\section{\(k\)-finite transport companions for the \(H^0\) bridges}
300	\label{sec:HModule_finite_zero_iter038}
301	
302	After the \(H^0\) bridges identify cohomology with Hom groups, the immediate companion is transport of finite-dimensionality: if the Hom group is finite-dimensional over \(k\), so is the cohomology group.
303	
304	\begin{theorem}\leanok
305	[\(k\)-finite transport for global \(H^0\)]
306	  \label{thm:Scheme_module_finite_HModule_zero}
307	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.module_finite_HModule_zero}
308	  
